lt. We stress that the stability result in [11] is the only analysis available in the literature for a numerical method approximating a dynamical model of fluidic biomembranes. Extending this analysis to a model that also includes energy contributions arising from the asymmetry of the membrane, i.e. spontaneous curvature and/or area difference elasticity contributions, is the goal of this paper. The remainder of the paper is organized as follows. In Section 2 we present the mathematical model that we wish to study in detail. Using ideas from PDE constrained optimization, we are able to derive a weak formulation in Section 3, which then allows for a semi-discretization (continuous in time, discrete in space) for which we can show a stability bound; see Section 4. The discretization is based on a parametric method for the interface, which is then coupled in an unfitted way to the bulk equations. The velocity and pressure in the bulk are discretized with the help of standard Taylor–Hood type elements. In Section 5 we introduce the fully discrete and fully coupled discrete system, for which we show unique solvability under appropriate assumptions. After a discussion of possible solution methods for the resulting linear systems in Section 6, we present several numerical computations demonstrating the practicability of the method and the effect of the asymmetry in the membrane in Section 7.


